Calculate the difference between critic and audience rating

In [213]:
movies_data["rating_diff"] = movies_data["audience_rating"] - movies_data["tomatometer_rating"]
movies_data["rating_diff_abs"] = movies_data["rating_diff"].abs() #absolute value
columns_of_interest = ["movie_title", "directors", "tomatometer_rating" , "audience_rating", "rating_diff", "rating_diff_abs"]
movies_data[columns_of_interest].head()
Out[213]:

4 20,000 Leagues Under The Sea Richard Fleischer 89 74 -15 15
5 10,000 B.C. Roland Emmerich 8 37 29 29

Note: rating_diff is audience - critic. That means a positive score means the audience liked it more than the critics. A negative score means the opposite.

Histogram of Movies by year of release¶

In [256]:
movies_data = movies_data[movies_data.in_theaters_date.notnull()]
movies_data['in_theaters_date'] = pd.to_datetime(movies_data['in_theaters_date'])
movies_data['movie_year'] = movies_data['in_theaters_date'].apply(lambda x: x.year)

sns.set(style="white")

plt.figure(figsize=(15,10))
plt.title('Movies by the year', size=20)
sns.distplot(movies_data.movie_year, kde=False)
plt.ylabel('Number of movies', size=15)
plt.xlabel('Year of release',size=15)
plt.axis([1920, 2019, 0, 1750])
plt.xticks(np.arange(1920, 2018, step=5),rotation=45, ha='right')
plt.show()

In [90]:
 #Create a crosstab of first_genre vs tomatometer_status
genre_rating_tomatometer = pd.crosstab(movie_genres_df.first_genre, movie_genres_df.tomatometer_status, margins=True)

# Loop through each genre and create a pie chart for the distribution of tomatometer_status
for genre in genre_rating_tomatometer.index[:-1]:  # Excluding the last row (margins)
    genre_data = genre_rating_tomatometer.loc[genre]  # Get data for a single genre
    genre_data = genre_data.drop('All')  # Remove the 'All' column
    
    # Plotting the pie chart for this genre
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    plt.pie(genre_data, labels=genre_data.index, autopct='%1.1f%%', startangle=90, colors=plt.cm.Paired.colors)
    plt.title(f'Distribution of TomatoMeter Status for {genre}')
    plt.axis('equal')  # Equal aspect ratio ensures that pie is drawn as a circle
    plt.show()

The EDA of the dataset reveals that the "tomatometer" status, categorized as "fresh," "rotten," or "certified," varies across different genres. Visualizations show that certain genres are more likely to have higher "fresh" ratings, while others lean toward "rotten." This analysis provides valuable insights into how movie genres relate to review scores.

Conclusion

This movie dataset analysis demonstrates the potential of machine learning in predicting movie ratings and genres. By leveraging features like movie info, critics' consensus, and release dates, models can accurately classify movies as "Rotten" or "Fresh" and predict audience ratings. Future work can explore incorporating additional features, comparing model performances, and applying these insights to real-world movie recommendation systems.
